segments.text: As far as you recall, about how much lead time warning did a young man get between the time he got his orders to report and the date he had to go?
Okay, now what happened when we were sophomores, they came out in the fall, they said if you would join the AF Armed Forces Reserve,
If you were joined that, you can stay in school until the end of your semester, end of sophomore year.
So we actually were enrolled in the Army while we were at A&M.
We weren't getting paid, but we were in the Army.
With understanding, we could stay until June, I guess.
So as soon as we were at school, we went straight to the Army.
So that's June of 43.
June of 43.
I went to Camp Maxitex.
All right.
That sophomore year, did you have a car?
Oh, no.
And you're still living on a pretty... Yeah, oh, yeah.
You mentioned a while ago you didn't have any civilian clothes your freshman year.
No, we didn't.
I had some, but they were in Stevensville.
But you didn't bring any with you?
No, no.
So that even if you had decided you wanted to slip off and wear some civilian clothes you didn't have any... That's right.
I was happy to wear that uniform.
You didn't have anything that had to go to the dry cleaners.
No.
It was all washable, wasn't it?
We had the laundry every week.
And we'd wear our clothes sometimes six weeks after.
It was dirty.
Now, you sent them to the laundry.
You didn't do them yourself.
They picked them up.
Did you wash your own socks and underwear?
Mm-hmm.
Where'd you get a haircut?
Over at the core area right there.
You know where the Trigon is?
On the opposite corner, south corner there.
Not south corner, the east corner.
There was a little shopping area right in there.
They had a barbershop, they had a little cafeteria type thing or drugstore, shoe shine place like that.
We ate there.
We got our haircuts there.
I didn't go up North Vegas.
And what kind of razor did you guys use?
I've always used straight razor.
I never used straight razor.
Okay, I was wondering.
I think my father maybe did, but they must have come out in the 30s because I never shaved with anything with straight razor.
Let's see, was Leupold around those days?
I do not remember because I didn't go to Northgate.
Okay.
How often did you go to Bryan?
Never.
Never?
I never went to Bryan all the time I was here until after I came back after the war.
Okay, we mentioned...
wartime events.
We mentioned Pearl Harbor.
What other events do you remember before you went on active duty that made an impression?
Bataan, Corregidor?
Names.
We didn't have the news.
We didn't have theaters.
We didn't get the news in those days.
You might have heard it on radio, but I don't recall.
It didn't make an impression.
So you don't go out for spring training then your sophomore year?
I went spring training sophomore year.
knowing you're not going to be here that far.
That's correct.
And Norton told us there, and that's one thing I've always loved him for.
He knew we was going.
Everybody knew we was going.
He said, I guarantee you guys, you'll have a scholarship when you come back.
And that cost him his job later.
I have heard that.
That got him fired.
He couldn't recruit young guys, so he's going 25, 26.
He's been gone three years, and we couldn't cut it.
But he let us come back and finish our education.
Let's see.
What were the most...
in those years, what were the most popular student indulgences?
On campus?
Drownouts?
I never saw this, but they used to unload the trains.
They had what they called Fish Day.
I think that's what they called it.
And that day the freshmen could get away with murder.
They could do anything.
And sometimes they told me that they'd go up here and stop the trains
and unloaded whatever they had on them.
I didn't see that, but I didn't get...
I don't remember any great... That was the first one.
Oh, the steam tunnels.
You know about steam tunnels.
Tell me about steam tunnels.
I never got in one, but I know what they did.
Well, now, nobody admits having been in them.
I never went in them.
I wouldn't know one, but they tell me... Lewis Buck.
Let me tell you about Lewis Buck.
What's the last name?
Buck.
He was a freshman football player.
Big guy, 220, 230.
We had a corps commander, and I do not remember his name, but Louis Buck beat him up.
When he was gone, they beat the hell out of him.
And I don't know if he went through the steam tunnel or not, but the senior corps, now the senior corps ran any of those things.
We didn't have commandants and all that stuff.
The seniors ran the college, I guarantee you.
They packed his stuff and put him on the train and told him never to come back on this campus.
Ever.
Well, of course, the war came.
He went to war, and he did come back and got a veterinary degree.
And he's a classmate of mine, class 45.
His sister was on one of the 10 most wanted criminals on the FBI list.
Well, Buck came back.
and got his degree, and then he got into, you know Les Palmer?
Sure.
He was Les Palmer's roommate.
Oh, okay.
We had our 50th reunion, and we had a meeting over at the motel, and the president came out and talked, and Buck would sit back, and he was so rude.
He was the rudest person I ever saw.
And then he went on up here to Franklin and died, but he's the guy that beat up this poor guy who was,
He came here from NTAC, North Texas.
But I never got in those things.
I wasn't going to get down in that hole.
Let's see, were you aware of any secret fraternities?
Yeah, I've heard they were.
I heard there's something called Sons of Texas or True Texans.
There's one called...
What was that other one?
They've been here forever.
But you weren't aware of who they were?
Not when I was in school.
I never heard of them.
No, I just heard of those after I came back working here.
I don't remember what they are.
Let's see.
Was there silver taps in those days?
Yes, but I never went.
I went to Silver Taps after I came back here, and I've only been one time.
And let's see, and you didn't go to Final Review before you went away to the service?
No.
Okay.
All right, you came back then when?
Came back in January 1946.
All right, so the war was over in August of 45, and you're here in January.
Had the campus changed?
Yes, of course.
A lot more people here, more civilians here, more girls here, wives.
So that big growth was already there in January?
Yes, I think so.
And the women, there was lots of women.
Of course, they couldn't go yet.
A lot of guys like I was were married and children on campus.
All right.
I have assumed that the typical student then was much more determined, much more goal-oriented.
Much less playing around then.
Oh yeah, definitely.
People are more mature.
Not much monkey business.
People wanted to get out.
They'd lost three years.
So you lived over, pretty soon you're over in College View.
Yeah.
And what did the wives do?
Well, I don't know.
But they had their own little group.
Some of them worked.
My wife didn't work.
She had a little boy.
And what kind of activities were there for the pre-first graders?
There was nothing like that.
There wasn't daycare?
They hung around that area and visited with young friends there at that time.
So we would go to school.
Well, I would go to school at 8 o'clock in the morning.
I wouldn't get home until 8 o'clock at night.
Now you're playing, did you play ball?
Yeah, played two more years.
And so you're going through two-a-days.
Yeah.
And let's see, is Coach Norton still?
Coach Norton's still here.
He went out when I went out, and Harry Stiler came in.
How many of your classmates, how many of those, in general, how many of those pre-World War II scholarship recipients came back?
Well, I've thought about that, Haskell.
I don't think that more than 10 of us ever graduated out of that 100 and something came here.
I could be.
Well, but not of that 100.
But those that were here in 42.
Came back?
Uh-huh.
Let me look here a minute.
Okay.
Came back.
Fulberg did.
He didn't.
He didn't.
That's Bill Sabian.
He didn't.
McCann didn't.
He didn't.
Henderson didn't.
Cure didn't.
Montgomery didn't.
Cullen didn't.
Zappalack didn't.
Leo did.
Jake Webster.
Williams.
He did.
He did.
These were here before.
Damon Tassus, Jennings Anderson, Vernon Valville.
I'd say about half of that bunch.
Okay, about half.
And I'm assuming that all of you were better students.
Definitely.
Because you were more mature.
Your goals were more clear.
You had greater responsibilities.
Did the faculty seem to understand that?
I don't know that I never had any problem with faculty people.
They were always very generous to me.
Was the faculty that you remembered, were many of them still here?
A few.
The main guy I can remember is Dan Russell.
He was really a great guy.
He helped students.
Of course, a lot of faculty people have been off to war, too.
There wasn't that much difference in our ages, too much.
And let's see, then after the war,
Do you remember any musters or those things?
No, I don't ever think I... We didn't have muster on the campus.
I don't think it started there yet.
All right, when you graduated, where was commencement held?
Dine.
Do you remember who the speaker was?
No, I didn't go because I graduated midterms.
And there was no commencement?
There was no commencement.
Okay.
And you stayed here?
Here.
Never left the campus.
Okay.
So you didn't do a final review.
No, I wasn't in the Corps.
Oh.
When I came back after the war, I was enlisted during the war.
Okay, so you dropped.
I was a staff sergeant first class, which is two stripes.
And I wanted to get back in the Corps and get my commission.
But I heard that after I got in college, they said if you leave here,
you won't have an apartment, so I couldn't go to summer camp.
So I said, okay.
So I went ahead and got a commission and had a deal then for your first three graders, then you could get commission, which I did.
And I got in the guard in those days.
Let's see.
Bonfire.
Was there a bonfire held?
I don't remember one.
I've seen pictures of it.
It was a bunch of little trashy boxes.
You don't even remember where it was?
The first one I remember is over in front of the MSC.
Now, you're not wearing an Aggie ring.
Yeah, I am.
Oh, I'm sorry.
And why is an Aggie ring important?
I don't know.
I think it just binds guys.
As you know, the first place I look, anywhere I go, I look at their fingers.
And I have run across Aggies everywhere just because of that ring.
I think it's just something with...
I came to A&M for a lot of reasons.
One was the boots and one for the ring.
I didn't get the boots because I didn't get the... See, my class, we never had a corps commander.
We never had a senior yell leader.
We never had a class president.
We didn't have any of that because we were gone when our time came.
So we're kind of a different class than most of them.
Class 45.
How many other classes would that be?
None, none of them.
Would the class of 44, though?
I don't think so.
Class 44, wouldn't some of them, wouldn't a large number of them have gone?
Yeah, I'm sure they would.
But 45, certainly.
But we didn't have any of that.
What makes Aggie Spirit what it is?
Well, the best I can say is I read the other day, he says, from within, you can't describe it without you can't understand it.
That's all I mean.
Are there any events that help?
Athletic, definitely.
Okay, but what else?
Well, if someone participates in civil tax, it does.
If you go to Smuster, it does.
Any of the things, the big things on the campus that do.
Friendship, binding together.
It's hard.
Now, like these two kids of hers,
And her two sons, I just feel so much closer to them because they're Aggies.
Aggies can do no wrong.
And I know that's wrong because some of them here I wouldn't have in my house.
But Mr. Penberthy used to say, these old guys came back here and they liked to talk about how it was in their day.
He says what they meant, they liked to talk about how they thought it was in their day.
So that's probably what I'm thinking.
You remember the good part.
I think these events...
that are comparatively inclusive.
Nobody checks your grade point ratio or anything before you walk in.
I think for some, fish camp helps to start them along that road now.
Even today, as crowded as it is, I think those activities are still inclusive.
Well, let's see.
I'm just about to finish.
What did it mean to you in terms of your life that you came to Texas A&M?
Well, I don't know.
I don't know anything else.
This has been my home for 67 years.
I think I was very fortunate to get to come here.
I was very fortunate I went to war and came back.
I was very fortunate that
But all the things that, like my first job here, all the friends I've made, the places I've been able to go, my children growing up here, although none of my children are Aggies.
I didn't go to school with them.
But I don't know.
It's just I couldn't think of being from anywhere else.
Again, it's hard for me to describe that.
It's awfully hard.
All right, let's make believe somebody gave you a million-dollar check that you had to give to A&M.
but you can decide what it's going to go for.
What would you have it?
It wouldn't go athletic.
What parts of the institution are dearest to you?
Well, I've thought about it.
If I ever won the lottery, I would give 10%.
I don't know if I wouldn't do it to the church.
And I got to thinking, how am I going to do it to the church?
So what do I think I'd do?
I'd give it to somebody in charge and say, you know more than I do where your needs are.
That's about all I could come up with.
Are there any, if all of the Aggies that you've ever encountered were available, which Aggies would you want to thank most?
Darius Moser, Paul Bernard, Ben McCollum, the man we haven't even talked about.
What did he do?
He was a man in Stephenville that was a banker.
He had both legs cut off here.
His son was an Aggie, a veterinarian, and he encouraged me to come here.
And a guy named Harry Breyer, who was also an Aggie in Stephenville, he encouraged me to come here.
Because I was searching where I wanted to go to school at that time.
I could have gone back wherever I wanted to at that time.
And neither one of you gave you any financial inducement?
No, no, no.
Is there anybody that you, if they were available, that you'd want to invite to come over and sit near you to enjoy a good life?
Some Aggie coming?
Yeah.
Spike White.
He's a best friend of mine.
I can tell in your voice while I go how you...
You know Bob?
You know his son?
He's a dentist.
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, he's our dentist.
Okay.
Well, see, I raised Bob.
You're talking about this fish camp.
Tim Burton is responsible for that.
Mr.
Gay, Garden Gay, you know what that means?
Oh, yes.
Garden Gay and Spike White and a guy named Napoleon, a black man who worked a while, and I took the first fish camp.
Up to Mahea.
Mahea.
Mahea.
We went there for years.
I went straight for 20-some odd years fishing there.
Oh, and not the one at Palestine.
No, no, it was later.
Palestine wasn't even there yet.
Where near Mahea?
Oh, at Fort, what's that Fort Mahea following?
Oh, oh, oh.
Fort Parker.
Fort Parker.
We went to Fort Parker.
Yes.
We had about 25 boys.
Now, when was that?
Early 50s.
Now, this was a fish camp.
We drove up there in a school bus.
How long did it last?
Two or three days?
About three days.
And what were the primary emphases?
Well, like they do today, I guess.
We took these kids up there.
They got to know one another.
We brought corps commanders in the upper class.
We brought faculty up there.
Student leaders up there and talked to the kids and helped them understand.
Get Yale leaders to come up.
They liked to do that.
Whose idea was it?
And Gordon Gates.
Where did they get that?
I don't know, but it never happened before.
They didn't come?
I don't know of any other school.
I don't know about that, but we went up there, and I remember I went until 1972, I guess.
In 1961, remember Carla?
Mm-hmm.
Remember Carla?
We were there then, and we had to leave early.
We had to rush home because we were afraid they were going to call us.
Because I've always thought that what fish camp does is to immerse everybody in maroon when they get to the campus as freshmen.
Gives them lots of information they need.
And again, it's one of those binding.
That's right.
Well, you live with people.
It doesn't take three or four days.
It's like, okay, so you came to Stephenville and I came to Myron as well.
So what?
Come on, we're in the same dorm, same...
So, last question.
What feelings do you hold in your heart for any of them?
I don't hold the feelings I had for my other friends.
I love A&M, what it does, but there's so many things I don't like.
I don't like homosexuals.
I don't like lesbians.
I don't like people coming in here and desecrating the campus.
I don't like people coming in here that never go to anything yet.
They want to go out and live on the traditions and the morals of A&M that other people have done.
They go out and say, I'm an Aggie.
I think this very strongly.
There's Aggies and there's students at Texas A&M, and I think there's a hell of a lot of difference.
And I think we're getting more and more students at Texas A&M to do Aggies.
I used to think only Aggies were poor, but I don't do that anymore.
But we've got a lot of guys here.
They're not Aggies.
They're just students passing through here, and I don't like that.
Because the people they're going out, they're representing A&M to other people.
I said, gosh, that's a great Aggie.
They're not even fair Aggies.
And I think it's getting worse and worse.
Like you said, we're too big.
We've lost touch.
I don't have the feeling.
I don't know if I'd come to him today.
